Certainly! Here's an updated bare minimum HTML template with a basic list, consisting of 4 rows:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>Page Title</title>
    <style>
        body {
            background-image: url("your-image-url-here");
            background-repeat: no-repeat;
            background-size: cover;
        }

        ol {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            padding: 0;
            margin: 0;
            list-style-type: none;
        }

        li {
            margin: 3em 0;
            font-size: 2em;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <ol>
        <li>Item 1</li>
        <li>Item 2</li>
        <li>Item 3</li>
        <li>Item 4</li>
    </ol>
</body>
</html>
```

In this updated template, we added a new `ol` style section to create a flexbox container with the `display`, `flex-direction`, `justify-content` and `align-items` properties. By setting `flex-direction` to `column`, the list items will be displayed vertically. The `height` property has been set to `100vh` to make the list take up the full height of the viewport, while the `padding` and `margin` are set to `0`, and the `list-style-type` is set to `none`. The `li` style section specifies font size and margin.

You can change the content of the list and adjust the properties of the `ol` and `li` tags as per your needs.

To import a font family in CSS, you can use the `@font-face` rule. Here's an example of how to import a font family named "Roboto" from Google Fonts into your CSS file:

```css
@font-face {
    font-family: 'Roboto';
    src: url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto&display=swap');
}
```

In this example, we're importing the "Roboto" font family from Google Fonts using the `url` property, and setting the `font-family` property to 'Roboto'. Once the font face has been defined using `@font-face`, you can use the "Roboto" font family in any CSS property, such as `font-family`.

Note that when importing a font family, you need to include the URL to the font file in the `src` property. You can usually find this URL on the website where the font is hosted, such as Google Fonts. Additionally, make sure to include the correct font family name in any CSS properties where you want to use the font.

The `@font-face` rule should be placed inside the CSS file, but outside of any CSS selector. This allows you to define the font family once and then use it in multiple places throughout your CSS.

For example:

```css
/* Import the font family */
@font-face {
    font-family: 'Roboto';
    src: url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto&display=swap');
}

/* Use the font family in a CSS selector */
body {
    font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.5;
}
```

In this example, the `@font-face` rule is defined at the top of the CSS file, before any selectors. Then, the font family is used in the `body` selector using the `font-family` property.

By defining the `@font-face` rule outside of any selectors, you can reuse the font family in multiple places throughout your CSS file without having to redefine it each time.

